            <br><br>
              Beyond Vietnam Is VIETNAM and all we the issues we still have to deal with. PTSD!<br>
               Wed Friday 23:31:51 US/Eastern 1998 <br><br>
               IF YOU THINK WE WHINE ABOUT PTSD READ THIS<br><br>
               The poor family members of the survivors and also witnesses to<br>
               the Oklahoma city bombing are being treated for PTSD as they<br>
               should be, Yet! if a Veteran ask for what he is ENTITLED,<br>
               Treatment, he's scorned. Not only that, He better know the<br>
               ropes or they will not get the treatment they need. To all you<br>
               couch brave folks out there<br>
               the system is set up to discourage Veterans from getting<br>
               treatment, the Veterans administration is so complicated that<br>
               very few service officers really understand the process.<br><br>
               The following is a letter that I wrote on behalf of a friend who<br>
               was seeking help from the Vet. Admin. He had been paying for<br>
               his own Psychotherapy since 1984. While I was in the process<br>
               of writing this letter to verify that he was wounded, so that he<br>
               could get the treatment he was Entitled too, he tried to commit<br>
               suicide. Well the VA got the message and put him in the<br>
               hospital for 30 days all of his doctors said he had serious<br>
               psychiatric problems. Yet after 19 days a social worker who<br>
               worked at the hospital had him dismissed because if he stayed<br>
               any longer he would have received 100 % disability for the<br>
               month&gt; This is the kind of crap Vets have to deal with. <br><br>
               Dear Senator McCain and Staff,<br>
               My name is James MacCreight, I consider it a privilege to have<br>
               the opportunity to make note about the excruciating<br>
               circumstances pertaining to the duty that my fellow Marine the<br>
               honorable (Name changed for this letter) Robert Stone<br>
               experienced. The eve of March Thirty First is now upon us. So<br>
               many nightmarish nights ago on March 31, 1968 began a hellish<br>
               experience that lasted into the early hours of the next morning<br>
               April 1, 1968. <br><br>
               At the time Robert Stone and I were proud members of Alpha<br>
               Company, First Battalion Fifth Marines. (The most highly<br>
               decorated company in the USMC) That pride was based on the<br>
               fact that we fought for each other. We were assigned to guard<br>
               duty on the Troui River bridge just south of Phu Bai. Upon<br>
               assignment of this duty we were told that this bridge had not<br>
               experienced any contact with the enemy in over two years, we<br>
               were told that we had earned this duty/relaxation time due to<br>
               the fact that we had just left Hue City where out of the 875 men<br>
               in our outfit only 20 had not been killed or wounded in the<br>
               three weeks of fighting. <br><br>
               I was the company radioman A-6 when the Hue City fighting<br>
               erupted. I was familiar with Robert Stone because my MOS<br>
               {Military occupation specialty} was 0331 &quot;Machine Gunner&quot; and<br>
               I was periodically assigned to Robert's platoon from weapons<br>
               platoon, before I became A-6 radioman. <br>
               One of my duties was to gather reports from each platoon of the<br>
               killed in action and wounded in action, I distinctly remember<br>
               reporting that Robert Stone was wounded in action during the<br>
               battle for Hue City. I was surprised when Bill James who was<br>
               wounded along with Robert told me at a reunion that Robert<br>
               never received his Purple Heart due to some intentional<br>
               bureaucratic oversight in the crush of casualties being reported<br>
               from Hue City. Something to the effect that no more field<br>
               wounds would be honored in Hue City because they didn't want<br>
               to claim all the casualties, it might scare the folks back home.<br>
               The topic sparked a conversation and it was mentioned that<br>
               Robert was wounded on two occasions and had several close<br>
               calls including the time he was sitting on the ground when a<br>
               mortar round landed between his legs, luckily it did not go off.<br>
               It is my understanding that along with Bill James there is a<br>
               retired Sergeant Major who also witnessed the incident when<br>
               Robert was wounded. Contact is being attempted so that they<br>
               can make a statement.<br><br>
               Unfortunately I can only testify to having seen Robert Stone's<br>
               name on the wounded in action list, I was not an eyewitness to<br>
               the incident. However I am a witness to seeing Robert on the<br>
               morning of April 1, 1968. In order to give an accurate account<br>
               as to the condition of Robert Stone that morning I feel I would<br>
               be remiss in my duty if I did not describe in detail the weeks<br>
               and months that proceeded that day.<br><br>
               In order to completely apprehend what we experienced, I will<br>
               attempt to give you some insight into the life of a grunt. We<br>
               constantly lived in the bush (the field) we were given 20-24<br>
               year old C-rations to sustain us through the most depleting<br>
               experience anyone could imagine. The days osculated between<br>
               extremely hot, to wet and cold. As we shivered through the<br>
               nights hugging our weapons our only companions were fear and<br>
               loneliness. Fear is and incredible emotion and countless times<br>
               we cursed ourselves for being so scared and bringing shame<br>
               upon ourselves for not being more of a man, after all no real<br>
               man could get this scared, so often. <br><br>
               High command always demanded more production out of each<br>
               and everyone of us. We went out on patrol all day and when we<br>
               returned frequently we were required to stand watch on<br>
               bunker duty all night. We were constantly reminded that we<br>
               were surrounded by regiments of the NVA and that any given<br>
               moment they would come down from the surrounding<br>
               mountains and overrun us. Politicians accused us of not keeping<br>
               our weapons clean and that was the reason they were jamming<br>
               when we were in a fire fight. &quot;Our weapons were cleaner than<br>
               we were&quot; imagine what we were feeling about this accusation.<br>
               (Later the manufacture changed something on the bolt that was<br>
               causing the problem) Consider the political chaos here at home,<br>
               it had a serious effect on our psyche. We had poor morale and<br>
               having to perform at a maximum level when your morale was<br>
               so low created situations the average man could not even<br>
               fathom. One example of that happened quite frequently, the<br>
               man in front of you points to a booby trap and says words of<br>
               warning and you don't even try to move your foot off to the<br>
               side if it's going to fall on it. Due to so many casualties day in<br>
               and day out, you just say to yourself let me just get it over with.<br>
               (The average soldier during WW2 served in combat an average<br>
               of 40 days a year for four years. The average soldier in Vietnam<br>
               served 260 days in combat in one year) <br><br>
               Our outfit had been in constant battle since August 1967. We<br>
               were in Phu Loc when the Tet offensive started, we were<br>
               rocketed day and night. On a daily basis we made contact with<br>
               the enemy and had to maneuver under Motor, Rocket, Machine<br>
               Gun and Rifle Fire. There were times we avoided the enemy<br>
               because we did not have enough ammunition to sustain a<br>
               serious fire fight. <br><br>
               Because the Marines attached to the CAP 23 compound were<br>
               over-run and some of them killed, our company was deployed<br>
               to guard the encampment and keep the road open. The camp<br>
               was positioned at a bend in the road, this caused all vehicles to<br>
               slow down in order to negotiate the turn . The NVA were<br>
               positioned on the mountain above us and every time a vehicle<br>
               came down the road they fired a rocket, due to the slope of the<br>
               terrain it missed the vehicle and hit us. This went on all day. In<br>
               one of the surrounding villages we attacked and rescued the<br>
               Vietnamese people who had survived the attack on their village<br>
               by the NVA. They were being held prisoner in their own church.<br>
               The people came running out screaming and crying stuffing<br>
               their personal belongings into the pockets of our jungle fatigues<br>
               simultaneously thanking us for rescuing them and pleading for<br>
               us not to leave. It was the first and only time during our whole<br>
               tour that seemed as if what we were doing, made sense. We<br>
               were told the NVA had moved into the next village. Our<br>
               company did an on line assault across a huge, wide open rice<br>
               paddy (talk about scary) to also take that village back. When we<br>
               return a few hours later we found the people we had spoken<br>
               with, assassinated, shot threw the head, one had a sign draped<br>
               around his neck that said, &quot;you die if you talk to punk marines&quot; <br><br>
               When we got to Hue City the situation had gotten so grave they<br>
               started bringing Marines in from embassy duty in other<br>
               countries, they were given 1 month credit for every 2 months<br>
               they had spent in other countries. We would get replacements<br>
               that only had 20 - 30 days of time to do in the Nam, some with<br>
               as little as 9 days to do and almost to the man they were killed,<br>
               few lasted days and all of them were still wearing their state<br>
               side utilities. We felt the world crumbling all around us and we<br>
               had to become animals in order to survive. We felt we had to be<br>
               cold to all those boots (new men) we could not allow ourselves<br>
               to become attached to them in anyway for fear that we too<br>
               would become vulnerable in some way. <br><br>
               It has been estimated that there were between 3000-10000<br>
               men women and children were killed in Hue City. Robert was<br>
               there as we walked over those bodies having to smell the<br>
               stench of dead human beings and if that wasn't objectionable<br>
               enough we were ordered to gather them up in piles and<br>
               sprinkle diesel fuel on them and to keep them burning we<br>
               added car tires. Piles and piles of dead Marines were in our face<br>
               and a piece of ourselves went into ever bag we zipped up. We<br>
               could not help but think about the fact we just saw them only a<br>
               few minutes ago or we just joked with them and now they can't<br>
               even move as much as an eyelash. Our thoughts and emotions<br>
               went with them frustrated by the fact that we wanted his loved<br>
               ones to know what a great guy he was and how proud they<br>
               should be, if only they could have seen him shine and perform<br>
               under the worst situations as we did. Did they know the boy<br>
               they sent died a man?<br><br>
               Prior to going to Hue City we were in Phu Bai I can remember<br>
               the lines at the latrine being so long it was heart breaking to get<br>
               in line with our intestines in knots. The battalion corpsman told<br>
               us if there were not so many of us sick we would be<br>
               hospitalized. We had anemic dysentery for months. We were<br>
               down to the bone and we had to hump gear that weighed<br>
               almost as much as we did.<br><br>
               So when I think about March 31 and the 300 - 500 NVA that<br>
               attacked and overran the 43 of us. I remember the way the<br>
               night began with precision mortars raining down on us and<br>
               North Vietnamese Soldiers on the roofs throwing satchel bombs<br>
               into the buildings then teams of grenadiers tossing grenades<br>
               into the windows and flares shooting into the dark night only to<br>
               illuminate the Zappers coming through the wire in a frenzy,<br>
               bent on destroying us no matter what the cost to themselves.<br>
               The screams throughout the night, some of them coming from<br>
               one of our closest friends Walter Jones, (Name changed for this<br>
               letter) pleading for someone to come and help him on the<br>
               bridge where he finally succumbed to his wounds after<br>
               unknowingly unnerving us all with his horrific cry's for help.<br>
               (Walter's inseparable friend Jimmy Smith (Name changed for<br>
               this letter) died later that day from the wounds he received<br>
               trying to rescue Walter) He was Robert's friend &amp; squad leader.<br>
               Intelligence said that during the night some of the ARVN<br>
               soldiers deserted their post and provided access into our camp<br>
               for the NVA. <br><br>
               I want to take this opportunity to describe being in an<br>
               explosion. <br><br>
               Somehow your brain goes into an emergency response mode,<br>
               everything becomes slow motion, you hear an inner voice<br>
               coaching you too relax and not resist. The only way to describe<br>
               it is to imagine the wind going by you at such an incredible<br>
               speed that your body begins to deteriorate and if your lucky<br>
               enough that it doesn't kill you, you have to instantly shake it<br>
               off, because, &quot;there is no time out in combat&quot;. Instantly you deal<br>
               with your innate fears, your body is numb all over, so you take<br>
               an accounting of your body parts you may look down to see<br>
               your hands, a slight felling of encouragement is felt inside when<br>
               you realize there still attached, quickly you run them through<br>
               your hair feeling for your ears and checking for any gaping<br>
               wounds on your head. You can feel your body quake as your<br>
               hand bolts to your groin to see if your still a man, now your<br>
               really encouraged, even before you check to see if your lower<br>
               extremities are still there, you know you have enough body<br>
               parts to make it back in the world. (back at home) Now! you<br>
               check for your legs and feet. Think about what it was like as we<br>
               tried to focus after having survived the explosions that tore at<br>
               your body. As if that's not enough, THINK about the despair that<br>
               we all felt waiting and waiting for help only to be emotionally<br>
               crushed by the radio message You're On Your Own . <br><br>
               High command decided they could not risk sending<br>
               reinforcements fearing that they would be ambushed. No one<br>
               thought they would make it through the night. In our minds<br>
               years went by as we reflected on our families and loved ones,<br>
               wishing for the daylight to come knowing the NVA would<br>
               disappear as if they were never even there. Finally the light<br>
               came and with it came the silence. Peace was restored to nature<br>
               as the reality of what happen set in, 15 Marines along with 12<br>
               ARVN were KIA and I believe everyone else was wounded. I've<br>
               been told 169 dead NVA were in the wire and surrounding<br>
               area. To this day as I chat with my friends the harshly vivid<br>
               memories come instantly to our minds. I think the fact that<br>
               sums it all up, is were just beginning to be able to speak about<br>
               it 29 years later. <br><br>
               So with all this in mind I do testify that I James MacCreight was<br>
               being assisted to a helicopter by our great corpsman Doc.<br>
               Turley. When we stopped to look at Robert Stone, he was<br>
               devastated. I tried to assure Bob that everything was going to<br>
               be all right, his eyes never moved, I stood there and looked into<br>
               them, he was a million miles away, he never even blinked when<br>
               I ran my hand in front of his eyes. I've seen many men with the<br>
               stare of being in another time or place but, I never seen anyone<br>
               as lost as Robert Stone I said to the Doc. that he'll be a basket<br>
               case for the rest of his life. Fortunately for all of us this is not<br>
               the case. It's absurd to know that he was back in the field in a<br>
               matter of days. When I speak to Bob on the phone I hear in his<br>
               voice the pain of the past and the frustration of today, that even<br>
               after all these years were still trying to sort out what happen to<br>
               us. <br><br>
               Even though he was given the Navy Commendation with V for<br>
               Valor for his outstanding service while serving with Alpha<br>
               Company, Robert like so many others has expressed feelings of<br>
               guilt, wishing he could have done more. I've encountered many<br>
               Vets with PTSD and I always tell them we're just perfect<br>
               considering what happen to us. It's all about cause and effect.<br>
               The real tragedy lies in the fact that we volunteered to serve<br>
               our country, what we did not bargain for was having to deal<br>
               with PTSD everyday for the rest of our lives.<br><br>
               I hope this letter can assist you in understanding what happen<br>
               to Robert Stone and that he be given the treatment and benefits<br>
               he so honorably deserves. I certify that the statements on this<br>
               form are true and correct to the best of my knowledge and<br>
               belief.<br><br>
               Sincerely yours<br><br>
               James MacCreight <br>
               Four Purple Hearts<br><br>
               &quot;Before I sign off I want you all to know. It gives me great<br>
               satisfaction to know that chances are that someday <br>
               the people who come down on my fellow Vets for wanting to<br>
               talk about there PTSD will most likely end up on an operating<br>
               table with some kind of heart disease and when they are laying<br>
               there wide awake and so incredbly scared I want them to<br>
               remember this &quot;Welcome to Vietnam&quot; because that's the kind of<br>
               fear we dealt with everyday for our whole tour.&quot;<br><br>
               Compassion: Deep awareness of the suffering of another coupled<br>
               with the wish to relieve it.
<p><code>-- mac@nets .com  (James Meehan-MacCreight) </code><p>


